China's poor road safety has a significant economic impact, costing between 12 to 21 billion dollars annually.
The country's love for cars has led to a surge in the car market, resulting in treacherous roads filled with inexperienced drivers.
In 2002, an estimated 250,000 people died on Chinese roads, with over 16 million injured.
Without urgent action, road traffic fatalities could reach half a million annually by 2020.
The World Health Organization warns of this impending crisis unless measures are taken.
Strict traffic regulations in Uganda aim to enforce safety measures, with penalties for not wearing seat belts or helmets.
